> A chickpea bowl is the epitome of plant-based perfection. In this one, Turkish-spiced
> chickpeas are roasted alongside onion wedges and grape tomatoes, then tossed with
> bright and tangy lemon zest. Veggies are served over a bed of fragrant basmati
> rice mixed with pistachios and golden raisins for texture and sweetness. And since
> the secret's always in the sauce, you'll finish things off with a drizzle of herby
> lemon hummus that brings all these flavors together. With so much to savor in one
> bowl, we guarantee any non-vegan dinner guests won't even miss the meat!

Adjust rack to top position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and
preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Zest and quarter @lemon{1}. Halve, peel, and cut @red onion{1} into 1⁄2-inch-thick
wedges; mince a few wedges until you have 2 tablespoons (4 tablespoons for 4).
Peel and mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}. Roughly chop @pistachios{1/2%ounce}.
Halve @grape tomatoes{4%ounce} lengthwise. Drain and rinse @chickpeas{1%unit};
pat very dry with #paper towels{}. Roughly chop @parsley{1/4%ounce} and
@chives{1/4%ounce}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @golden raisins{1%ounce} with juice from one lemon
wedge (two wedges for 4).

== Rice ==

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tsp} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat.
Add minced onion, garlic, half the pistachios (save the rest for serving), half
the @Turkish Spice Blend{1%tablespoon} (you'll use the rest in the next step),
and a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Cook, stirring, ~{1%minute}.

Stir in @basmati rice{1/2%cup}, 3⁄4 cup water (1 1⁄2 cups for 4 servings),
@veggie stock concentrate{1%unit}, and a big pinch of salt. Bring to a boil,
then cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until rice is tender,
~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to use in step 5.

== Chickpeas and Veggies ==

Meanwhile, toss onion wedges, tomatoes, and chickpeas on a #baking sheet{} with
a large drizzle of oil, remaining Turkish Spice Blend, a few pinches of salt, and
@pepper{}. (For 4 servings, use 2 baking sheets; roast on top and middle racks,
swapping rack positions halfway through.)

Roast on top rack, tossing halfway through, until veggies are lightly charred
and chickpeas are crispy, ~{18-20%minutes}. (It's natural for chickpeas to pop
a bit while roasting.)

== Hummus Sauce ==

While everything roasts, in a #second small bowl{}, combine @hummus{4%tablespoon},
half the parsley and chives, @olive oil{2%tablespoon} (4 tablespoons for 4),
and juice from one lemon wedge (two wedges for 4). Season with salt. Stir in
water 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

== Barramundi ==

Pat @barramundi{10%ounce} dry with paper towels; season with salt and pepper.
Heat a drizzle of oil in a large, preferably nonstick pan over medium-high heat.
Cook barramundi (skin sides down) until skin is crisp, ~{4-5%minutes}, then flip
and cook until cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} more. Transfer to a #plate{}.

> You can substitute chicken for barramundi if you prefer. For chicken, cook about
> 3-5 minutes per side until cooked through.

== Assembly ==

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in raisins and their pickling liquid and remaining
parsley and chives. Season with salt and pepper.

Toss veggies and chickpeas with lemon zest.

Divide rice between shallow #bowls{} or #plates{}. Top with veggies and chickpeas.
Drizzle with hummus sauce to taste. Garnish with remaining pistachios and a squeeze
of lemon juice to taste. Serve with any remaining lemon wedges on the side.

Serve barramundi atop bowls.